spec: ab3211
version: ">=3.9"
backend: python_module(abc)

docs: https://docs.python.org/3/library/abc.html

provenance:
  derived_from:
    - "https://docs.python.org/3/library/abc.html"
    - "Test vectors verified with Python 3.14.4 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-13"
  not_derived_from:
    - "CPython source code"
    - "any proprietary source"
  notes:
    - "Wave 661 (ab3211): __and__, __or__, __xor__ dict-presence for abc module types."
    - "All values verified with Python 3.14.4 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-13."
    - "Classes covered: abc.ABC, abc.ABCMeta, and type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) — the built-in function type."
    - "Key finding (__and__): all 3 abc subjects return false for __and__. abc.ABC is a plain abstract base class helper with no arithmetic or bitwise semantics — ABC & n is not a defined operation. abc.ABCMeta is a metaclass responsible for abstract method tracking and virtual subclass registration (__subclasshook__, register(), __abstractmethods__); none of these capabilities involve bitwise AND. The function type (type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) is <class 'function'>) does not define __and__ — functions are callables and descriptors, not integer or set-like types. f & g is not a valid Python expression for function objects."
    - "Key finding (__or__): all 3 abc subjects return false for __or__. The Python 3.10+ union-type | operator (PEP 604) is implemented at the metaclass level via type.__or__ — it does not cause abc.ABC or abc.ABCMeta to define __or__ in their own __dict__. abc.ABCMeta is a metaclass for abstract base class machinery, not a set-like or collection type; | is not defined for metaclass instances. The function type does not define __or__; f | g is not a valid Python expression for function objects."
    - "Key finding (__xor__): all 3 abc subjects return false for __xor__. Bitwise XOR (^) applies to integers (bit-flip) and sets (symmetric difference). abc.ABC has no numeric or collection data model. abc.ABCMeta handles class hierarchy and abstract method tracking; none of its capabilities map to XOR. The function type does not define __xor__; f ^ g is not a valid Python expression for function objects."
    - "All 9 values in this wave are false — continuing the all-false pattern from wave 660 (__pow__/__lshift__/__rshift__)."
    - "The function type profile across all waves: true only for __get__ (wave 652), __repr__ (wave 655), and __call__ (wave 656). All other dunders tested — including this wave's __and__/__or__/__xor__ — are false."
    - "abc.ABCMeta has now returned false for every arithmetic and bitwise dunder tested across 10 consecutive waves (652–661). Its entire capability is expressed through class-hierarchy machinery, not operator overloading."
    - "Cross-wave summary for abc subjects:"
    - "  Wave 652 (ab3076): __get__ true for function type; __set__/__delete__ false."
    - "  Wave 653 (ab3091): __hash__/__eq__/__bool__ all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 654 (ab3106): __lt__/__le__/__gt__ all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 655 (ab3121): __ge__ false; __repr__ true for function type only; __str__ false."
    - "  Wave 656 (ab3136): __call__ true for function type only; __len__/__getitem__ false."
    - "  Wave 657 (ab3151): __setitem__/__delitem__/__contains__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 658 (ab3166): __add__/__sub__/__mul__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 659 (ab3181): __truediv__/__floordiv__/__mod__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 660 (ab3196): __pow__/__lshift__/__rshift__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 661 (ab3211): __and__/__or__/__xor__ — all false for all 3."
  created_at: "2026-04-13"

error_model: python_exceptions

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# __and__ dict-presence — operator.contains(Cls.__dict__, '__and__')
#
# All 3 abc subjects return false for __and__.
# abc.ABC: a plain abstract base class convenience wrapper with no arithmetic
#   or bitwise semantics. ABC & n is not a defined Python operation.
# abc.ABCMeta: a metaclass for abstract method tracking and virtual subclass
#   registration. None of these responsibilities map to bitwise AND.
#   ABCMeta's entire capability is in __subclasshook__, register(), and
#   __abstractmethods__ — not in operator overloads.
# type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) is <class 'function'>:
#   functions do not define __and__. f & g is not a valid Python expression
#   for callable objects. Functions are callables and descriptors — no
#   integer or set-like behavior is defined.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

table ab3211.and_:
  description: "abc types __and__ dict-presence checks; wave 661"
  kind: python_call_eq
  version: ">=3.9"
  error_model: python_exceptions
  category: dict_contains
  id_prefix: ab3211

  columns: [id, function, args, expected]
  rows:
    - ["ab3211001", operator.contains, [abc.ABC.__dict__,                                 "__and__"], false]
    - ["ab3211002", operator.contains, [abc.ABCMeta.__dict__,                             "__and__"], false]
    - ["ab3211003", operator.contains, [type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)).__dict__,  "__and__"], false]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# __or__ dict-presence — operator.contains(Cls.__dict__, '__or__')
#
# All 3 abc subjects return false for __or__.
# abc.ABC: no bitwise OR protocol; abstract base classes are not integer
#   or set-like types. ABC | n is not a defined operation.
# abc.ABCMeta: does not define __or__ for metaclass union or type annotation
#   purposes. The Python 3.10+ union-type | syntax (PEP 604, X | Y type hints)
#   is implemented via type.__or__ on the type metaclass — it does not place
#   __or__ in abc.ABCMeta's own __dict__. ABCMeta's class registration
#   protocol uses register() and __subclasshook__ — not | operators.
# type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) is <class 'function'>:
#   functions do not define __or__. f | g is not a valid Python expression
#   for callable objects.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

table ab3211.or_:
  description: "abc types __or__ dict-presence checks; wave 661"
  kind: python_call_eq
  version: ">=3.9"
  error_model: python_exceptions
  category: dict_contains
  id_prefix: ab3211

  columns: [id, function, args, expected]
  rows:
    - ["ab3211004", operator.contains, [abc.ABC.__dict__,                                 "__or__"], false]
    - ["ab3211005", operator.contains, [abc.ABCMeta.__dict__,                             "__or__"], false]
    - ["ab3211006", operator.contains, [type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)).__dict__,  "__or__"], false]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# __xor__ dict-presence — operator.contains(Cls.__dict__, '__xor__')
#
# All 3 abc subjects return false for __xor__.
# abc.ABC: no bitwise XOR protocol. ABC ^ n is not a defined Python
#   expression. abc.ABC is a bare metaclass convenience wrapper with no
#   state of its own beyond what ABCMeta provides.
# abc.ABCMeta: does not define __xor__ for metaclass XOR. ABCMeta is a
#   powerful metaclass, but its API surface (__subclasshook__, register(),
#   __abstractmethods__) has no bitwise or set-algebra component.
# type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) is <class 'function'>:
#   functions do not define __xor__. f ^ g is not a valid Python expression.
#   The function type is tightly scoped to its role as a callable descriptor
#   with a display representation — no bitwise operators are defined.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

